Example \(\PageIndex{2}\) Match each equation with its graph. \[{f(x)=2(1.3)^{x} }
onumber\] \[{g(x)=2(1.8)^{x} }
onumber \] \[{h(x)=4(1.3)^{x} }
onumber \] \[{k(x)=4(0.7)^{x} }
onumber\] Solution The graph of \(k(x)\) is the easiest to identify, since it is the only equation with a growth factor less than one, which will produce a decreasing graph. The graph of \(h(x)\) can be identified as the only growing exponential function with a vertical intercept at (0,4). The graphs of \(f(x)\) and \(g(x)\) both have a vertical intercept at (0,2), but since \(g(x)\) has a larger growth factor, we can identify it as the graph increasing faster.

